Triumph of the populist right in Austria, together they make up 29%
Early elections to the Austrian parliament have led to the earliest results, an appreciable weakening of both parties of the current grand coalition, and an expressive strengthening of the populist right party.
Heavy and special losses have suffered by the Austrian People's Party (OVP), where the position of the current president, Wilhelm Molterer, is seriously reeling.
Instead, the leader of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZO), the head of carinthia's state government, J. Haider, is preparing his triumphant return to national politics.
According to the approximate results, social democracy (SP) remains the strongest party in the country with 29.8 percent votes, losing a 5.5 percent vote compared to the last election of 2006.
Worse, the OVP has ended, losing 25.6 percent, nearly nine percent of the vote.
They are the worst results, literally catastrophic, in the history of these two major Austrian parties since the post-war period and especially for the popular ones who called this early election.
Even in early July, when the OVP left the coalition, the popular had a considerable advantage when it came to preference over the SPO.
It is clear, however, that voters punished them for letting the government shipwreck.
Already in the first reactions to the results, speculation was heard about the resignation of the party president and, to this day, deputy chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe this could be reached at the party presidency's exceptional meeting on Monday.
Such developments would obviously facilitate the path of the constant and more approximate starting point of election results, i.e. the renewal of the grand coalition between SPO and OVP.
Given that the reinforcement of both parties on the populist right - the Liberals (FPO) have won about 18 percent and BZO, eleven percent of the vote - and that the Social Democrats at the same time expressed their fears that the same thing would be repeated from 1999 when the popular negotiated with the populists (then FPO was a unit , but in 2005 it was demearated from BZO) for a coalition government that came to generate a sanction on the part of the European Union.
For this evolution, Haider, who has already announced that he is ready to collaborate with any party and who is already taking his return to Vienna, to national politics, is clearly committed.
The Green Party has also managed to reach parliament although it has lost slightly and was relegated from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
No other party clearly exceeded the four per cent limit and is therefore not part of parliament.
