Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market led to a significant price decline to which classical operators had to react as well.
At the same time, even before sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the British market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It was shown that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
Otherwise, you don't have to look for examples too far.
In February of this year we inform you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
After only half a year, this operator managed to obtain more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on many more specific target groups.
In addition, much fewer customers than a classic operator can function effectively.
They do not bear relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world such virtual operators usually come up with low expenses - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that however, are often counteracted with the offer of tighter services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Britain offers at least half as cheap SMS from the competition.
However, as Mobilking's example in Poland shows, it can also be a good blow to a trivial goal group.
This operator is specifically aimed at man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - he's the operator he likes and who can be trusted," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
