The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of Nissan accident prevention technologies, it has been inspired, this time, by nature, in particular, by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, prevents accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C which is the first step in collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, General Manager of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan's four-area Security Shield.
This robot intends to strengthen the collision prevention capability of the brand's vehicles.
During its flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that looks a lot like the Nissan Safety Shield.
But the most important thing is the compound eyes of the bee, able to see with an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, allowing you to fly without interruption within your own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers designed what they have called a Laser Range Finder.
It detects obstacles up to two metres away within a 180-degree radius in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to that object, and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor that immediately results in collision prevention.
"The moment you detect an obstacle, the small robot will mimic a bee's movements and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at right or greater angles to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is that the evasion maneuver is completely instinctive.
If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and principal engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be deflected up or down, or diagonally; You can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allow you to turn your wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, as well as acceleration and deceleration, for the small robot to avoid collisions.
"This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It doesn't require saving information or intuitive logic from previous maneuvers, so it can work continuously with just a couple dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, not even megas."
This is the first step in developing new instant collision prevention technologies, a technology that Nissan predicts will be introduced to standard cars in ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the lithium-ion variety.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to their destination avoiding obstacles along the way.
