Talking in your sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean these who wake up very smart telling us something that happened the day before, but children who talk in their sleep.
The first time it happens, you might get a scare, but it doesn't really matter.
Sleep disturbance is a benign sleep disturbance called somniloquis.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one of them have been told he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in a lifetime for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once in meseS...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines its occurrence.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal enuresis (peeing asleep) or sleepwalking, but it doesn't have to be.
As mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever conditions, stress or overexcitement situations.
It's a little-studied phenomenon anyway.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
You may speak in a quiet tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or the opposite (screams, cries, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there are any issues that are generating a lot of anxiety and gives him exit in this way.
We have said that it is a benign alteration, therefore it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disturbance that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress picture).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
Therefore look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are scary or a little violent.
With very nervous children who have a hard time relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will help the child to have a quieter sleep.
Once the somniloquias appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything that has happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless, because he's not conscious, and you'll break his sleep.
Even if he's talking, he's sleeping and therefore he's resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed during several episodes, you may want to consult or find out what generates so much anxiety in the child.
