Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, vice president and director of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the largest gold company in the world attempted a six million euro defamation process against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a "transparent public debate."
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of defamation prosecutions, but the law.
Without surprise, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to harm whoever dares to hold a position contrary to theirs?
The outcome of the lawsuit is of little importance, the authors and publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers held by the miner's almost bottomless pockets.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will gag at the opposition as well as frighten whoever will dare to re-examine the issue.
If Barrick Gold had really wanted a public debate, it is in front of the public that he would have had to present his vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several of the countries where Barrick Gold works, discussions in Canada are usually done by changing ideas and not by blushing.
It was therefore sufficient for the miner to open her books, her files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the financing of independent search teams that could have clarified the issue.
But Barrick Gold doesn't seem to trust public opinion and rejects supporting requests and letters for Noir Canada authors.
Could Mr. Garver possibly explain how he can ask for a "public" debate by disresezing his views?
According to the vice president, it seems that this word refers only to highly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What he doesn't understand - or what he doesn't want to understand - Barrick Gold, is that the audience that supports Noir Canada's authors and publishers does so mostly because it rejects the miner's brutal manner.
This audience is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but based on civilized changes in arguments, and not within the framework of what many people perceive as a persecution-gag (chasing the "public debate," Barrick Gold has just filed a request regarding Noir Canada's authors by encouraging them not to use this word anymore).
In addition to Mr. Garver's surreal speech, The Barrick Gold process is a direct attack on university freedom of search and truth, essential for all democratic societies.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and argue about subjects who displease rich companies in this world in a country like Canada, under penalty of many persecutions, who can do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, he could do so in accordance with the scientific standards used by The Authors of Noir Canada.
You have a right of reply.
The university world, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive pursuit clearly shows that, contrary to what he intends, he does not feel like a transparent debate.
It is a loss to the university world, but also to public debate in Canada, and it is high time that governments put up devices that limit this genre of abusive persecution.
