The name hepatitis is the common name for different liver diseases caused by viruses.
Symptoms look a lot alike; Liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but its pathogens and diseases are very different.
Hepatitis viruses depending on the pathogen are spread in two main forms: hepatitis A and E foodbornely (e.g. with water or food spread), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body moods (sperm, vagina mood, saliva).
Travellers are recommended to protect themselves by vaccine against virus A and B, against C there are no vaccines.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifested by poor general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After this appear on the skin and on the white of the eyes jaundice, the excrement becomes light, the urine dark color and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Every year one million people die worldwide in cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most severe forms of hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten infected receives drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can cause liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Therefore it is very important premature recognition, systematic medical control.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusion before 1991, drug users, and those with tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people worldwide with chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with routine laboratory monitoring as well, it is worth consulting with your family doctor when experiencing any unknown symptoms.
The disease is cured if discovered early, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so that contagion can be suppressed and cancer prevented.
30 September is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
It aims to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of premature recognition.
