Does it hurt less to those who believe in God?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith has a calming effect that also alleviated the death of Catholicism's martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed how religious belief influences human pain - the British telegraph newspaper reported.
As part of this unique experiment, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were being electric shocked, while everyone was looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first in the series of research in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University also participate.
The analysis occurred as follows; they attached a sparkling instrument to the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the experiment participants to look at two paintings; to the Virgin Mary, the work of Sassoferrato of the 17th century and the Lady of leonardo da Vinci's ermine of the 15th century.
The researchers hoped that the spectacle of the Virgin Mary would provoke a certain religious spirit among the faithful, as they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and thought it had a reassuring effect.
Patients spent half an hour on an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts while observing religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics claimed that as they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt in "security" as "protected" people, "calmed down and peace reigned in their hearts."
Looking at the religious theme chart, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so shocking you can achieve such an effect with the atheists as well, you only have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person they feel very positively about, like a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases really changes our personality," Wright added.
After these formidable results, there is only one question: what effect would it have on pain regulation if the faithful were shown Leonardo's Madonna or another painter of his size?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
