Smart car mimics bumblebee flight
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of obstacle sensors existing in nature?
For example, that of bumblebees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, bumblebees provided the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
The Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the robotic car steering system type BR23C imitator of nature, which was given the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can dodge all collisions.
During the flight each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, Chief Technology Director of RP and Development and Research.
The compound eyes of bumblebees that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees play an important role.
To copy the composite eye function, engineers used the laser length measurement system.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance, and sends a signal to the vehicle's microprocessor that immediately transforms into a maneuver to prevent collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle robot mimicking the movements of the bumblebees, modifies the direction by turning the wheels to the extent necessary.
Unlike any existing system today, this maneuver is completely instinctive.
"If not, the vehicle robot couldn't react quickly enough to dodge obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Lab and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bumblebee does to dodge other bumblebees.
This process should be done in the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed up, down or diagonal, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bumblebees to dodge other bumblebees, here they only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotating movement and acceleration in addition to the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and their energy density is higher, which means they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the processing capacity of the data, let alone the storage.
This device in every second should only process some input signals and react as the case may be.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with instinctive logic based on the data from previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No gigabyte or megabyte memory is required.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately dodge obstacles, which according to Nissan calculations, within ten years can be incorporated into mass-produced models.
Another possibility for your application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to their destination, dodging the obstacles existing in their path.
