Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1% compared to last month's prices and 12.9% compared to August 2007 prices - the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1% compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9% compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7% compared to the previous month and 3.2% from the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased by only a minimum, at 0.1%.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry sectors increased minimally, by 0.1% compared to July.
The biggest increase in price magnitude occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 per cent), mainly due to a 4.6 per cent monthly increase in bags and belts and a 2.5 per cent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the industry's prices of chemical materials (1.6%).
There was a price decline in the petrochemical sector , (1.4 per cent), in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 per cent).
They did not change the prices of paper manufacturing, publishing and printing.
In the other sectors of the processing industry, prices increased by between 0.2 and 0.9%.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent a significant weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3% was recorded in August, firstly as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from the first of July.
In a twelve-month comparison - in domestic sales in the processing industry sectors - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4%).
In the metal processing sector, an increase of 13.2% was observed, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of decisive weight, there was an increase of 11%.
Prices were lowered in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In all other processing sectors, the pace of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
Over the past year in the global processing industry, prices increased by 10.2%.
Prices for electricity, gas, heat and water supplies exceeded previous year's prices by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade the largest monthly price increase (0.7%) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3%, in the prices of the energy sector and intermediary sectors there were no changes from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediary industry (16.8%).
Consumer goods-producing industries declined by 6.8 per cent and investment goods by 1.4 per cent.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF increased by 1.1% compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9%.
The price of our national currency in one month fell by 1.7% against the euro and by 7.1% against the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5% against the euro and 15.9% against the dollar.
