Fox in the chicken coop
In the United States, life and health insurance companies, when viewing drug purchase data, often deny signing an insurance contract.
Privacy policy specialists fear that the personal data market will be made uncontrollable.
"There are programs for the protection of personal data, which to the use of prescription data in all cases brings it together with the approval of the given person.
It must be in separate hands, because if not, "we entrust the chicken coop to the fox" - quotes the Washington Post to Richard Dick, designer of the prescription tracking program.
Insurance companies make the insurance price and compensation amount dependent on the customer's health status and if they believe the risk is excessive, they simply do not make the contract.
Previously they sent the client to medical control and signed with him the contract knowing already the result of the control.
Dick ten years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: with the customer identification number he easily gets from pharmacies the list of drugs purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself concludes on the diseases and health status of the client.
For example, if you systematically take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that the level of fat in your blood is virtually incurably high, so you are immediately included in a higher risk category.
Numerous versions of the program circulate, some even set a number of risks, so the insurance company in addition to management has little to do, although there are small difficulties in this regard.
Among the disadvantages of the program is for example that some medications are multipurpose, for example certain substances serve both to treat headache, heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is an important risk increase factor for insurance companies while the former are not.
Special companies were formed to consult and process this data, which before acquiring the necessary information from the pharmacies, ask for the approval of the patient.
The authorities are already forcing them to do so, although they were not fined for negligence so far.
Some companies have recently also produced the results of laboratory tests and by joining them with drug consumption data, they get more accurate information about the patient's health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and simultaneously it is becoming increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and those that provide health services.
The bill providing the right to the authority for the control of specialized companies for the provision of personal data is already before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is insufficient: he therefore developed his program, which will require the person's specific approval for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another issue that such a person cannot deny his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the hens, however, are exposed to the goodwill of the fox.
